<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-062-071 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 260 865</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Sept 9 1991 n368 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Onus is on users to pay for toll fraud. (long distance companiesdemand account owner pays for abuse)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gareiss, Robin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>All three major long distance telephone companies agree that thebusiness account holder is liable for any fraudulent calls made onthat companies' PBX (private branch exchange) equipment.andP;  ATandamp;T hassued no less than 17 major business customers for money that thecompany says it is owed, including Concurrent Computer Corp,Proctor and Gamble Co, and ITT Consumer Financial Corp. Analystsestimate that $3 million a day is lost to telephone fraud, andthat ATandamp;T's share could be two-thirds of that.andP;  MCI CommunicationsCorp and US Sprint Communications Co also suffer from huge lossesdue to phone abuse, and while neither company has actually suedany account-holders to date, both companies expect the businessesto pay for the calls.andP;  The telephone companies feel that they haveno alternative but to take legal action if companies refuse topay.andP;  Some analysts believe that should the telecommunicationcarriers merely absorb the losses, basic long distance rates wouldhave to be increased to cope with the huge deficit.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Cases).andO;Topic:     Legal IssuesFraudPBXLong-distance telephone servicesComputer crimesTelephone companiesComputer hackersLaw Suit.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   ATandamp;T sues its customers. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>